<paragraph id="3F070329FF89864DD9A8C579FBFC7A12" blockId="95.[136,778,1397,2070]" lastBlockId="95.[810,1452,1397,1832]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
The new species is also similar in many aspects with 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF89864DD9D7C55CFDDA7AB8" authority="Gilbert &amp; Hubbs, 1916" authorityName="Gilbert &amp; Hubbs" authorityYear="1916" box="[194,573,1907,1934]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="weberi">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF89864DD9D7C55CFED77ABB" box="[194,304,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. weberi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF89864DD82DC55CFDDA7AB8" author="Gilbert, C. H. &amp; Hubbs, C. L." box="[312,573,1907,1934]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" pagination="135 - 214" refId="ref285931" refString="Gilbert, C. H. &amp; Hubbs, C. L. (1916) Report on the Japanese macrourid fishes collected by the United States fisheries steamer &quot; Albatross &quot; in 1906, with a synopsis of the genera. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 51, 135 - 214, pls. 8 - 11. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.51 - 2149.135" type="journal article" year="1916">Gilbert &amp; Hubbs, 1916</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
known only from the 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF89864DD9A2C5BEFEFE7A85" box="[183,281,1942,1968]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">holotype</typeStatus>
collected from the 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF89864DDB1EC5BEFD6A7A85" box="[523,653,1942,1968]" name="Philippines" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Philippines</collectingCountry>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF89864DD99DC590FED77AE7" box="[136,304,1976,2002]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lanceolatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF89864DD99DC590FED77AE7" box="[136,304,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. lanceolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily distinguished from the latter species in that free neuromasts on the underside of the head are unpigmented and difficult to distinguish without a microscope (vs. each neuromast marked with two small black dots). It further differs notably from 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF89864DDC22C7B0FA4C7884" authorityName="Gilbert &amp; Hubbs" authorityYear="1916" box="[1335,1451,1431,1458]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="weberi">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF89864DDC22C7B0FA4C7884" box="[1335,1451,1431,1458]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. weberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a longer snout (107% PRL vs. 80%), shorter postorbital (53% PRL vs. 58%), and lower first dorsal fin (84% PRL vs. 99%). A pronounced difference between the two species was also found in the snout shape. In 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF89864DDC87C408FC4C7B6E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lanceolatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF89864DDC87C408FC4C7B6E" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. lanceolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the anterolateral margins of the snout are almost straight when viewed dorsally, giving a sharply pointed and distinctly attenuated appearance to the snout, whereas those of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF89864DDAE1C480FB837BF4" authorityName="Gilbert &amp; Hubbs" authorityYear="1916" box="[1012,1124,1703,1730]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="weberi">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF89864DDAE1C480FB837BF4" box="[1012,1124,1703,1730]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. weberi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are broadly convex so as to give a spade-shaped appearance to the snout. The latter species will be fully redescribed in a forthcoming paper by the present author.
</paragraph>
